******
[1] Nevada (Elko County)
Date: Thu 30 Oct 2014
Source: Elko (NV) Daily Free Press [edited]
http://elkodaily.com/news/pertussis-outbreak-in-elko-county/article_f30bc607-9aea-5462-b5cb-1d5cff469f70.html


The Division of Public and Behavioral Health has declared an outbreak of pertussis (whooping cough) in Elko County as of 20 Oct 2014. According to its data, Elko County has seen a rise in pertussis cases over recent years. As of Mon 27 Oct 2014, Elko County has had 14 cases of pertussis reported since July 2014. Controlling the spread of pertussis requires quick identification of cases and contacts prompt treatment of these individuals, and immunization of susceptible persons.

Pertussis spreads easily through the air when an infected person breathes, coughs, or sneezes. A person can spread the disease while he or she has cold-like symptoms and for at least 2 weeks after coughing starts. Vaccination of persons who are not up-to-date for pertussis provides long-term protection. Getting your child the vaccine helps protect them against whooping cough. It also protects other people who cannot get the vaccine, especially newborn babies, who can get very ill and can die from this infection. The division asks that you make sure your family's vaccinations are up-to-date. Older children and adults, including pregnant women, should get a pertussis booster shot called to protect themselves and infants near or around them. If you need the vaccine, contact your doctor. Early treatment of pertussis is very important. If treatment for pertussis is started early in the course of illness, during the 1st one to 2 weeks before coughing attacks occur, symptoms may be lessened.

